Secrets, like config maps but for sensitive data.

A secret is the same idea as a config map, plus a handful of differences that exist because the data is sensitive. Let us walk through what is different.

Storage in the manifest. Secret values are written either under data, already base sixty four encoded, or under string data, as raw text that the ay-pee-eye server base sixty four encodes for you before storing. A config map does not bother with base sixty four for strings.

In memory mounting. When a secret is mounted as a volume, the kube-let puts it on a ram backed filesystem, so it never touches the node's disk.

Storage in et-see-dee. By default, secret data sits in et-see-dee as base sixty four, which is not encrypted. Most production clusters enable an encryption configuration so the ay-pee-eye server encrypts secret data before writing it to et-see-dee. The exam expects you to know this is optional but recommended, and that it is the ay-pee-eye server, not et-see-dee itself, doing the encryption.

Are-back defaults. Many cluster role definitions deliberately exclude secrets from, read everything in this namespace. By policy, treat secrets as more sensitive than config maps, even though the underlying object kind is similar.

And now the single most important fact about secrets. Base sixty four is encoding, not encryption. Anyone who can read the secret object can decode it instantly. It is not a secret from someone with read access. It only stops the value from sitting in plain sight in a yaml file. Real protection comes from encryption at rest plus tight are-back, which we cover later.
